<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Chicken Note</div>
<div class="nbunit" id="edn57">  57  An illustrated guidebook, <cite>A Pictorial and Descriptive Guide to Bognor, Chichester, Selsey, Goodwood, Hayling Island, Midhurst, Arundel, Amberley, Petworth, &amp;c</cite> (London, 1922-1923), traced by Peter Timmerman, &lsquo;The First Guide to <cite>Finnegans Wake</cite>,&rsquo; <cite>AWN</cite> 16 (June, 1979) 45-48), tells us that in the graveyard of the old Early-English Church in Sidlesham are gravestones bearing such &lsquo;curious names&rsquo; as Earwicker, Gravy, Glue, Boniface, Anker, and Northeast.&rsquo; Joyce was in Bognor on holiday in the summer of 1923 shortly before he began work on I.2&sect;1 (&lsquo;Here Comes Everybody&rsquo;) and he had to hand a copy of the <cite>Guide</cite>. <i>Inter alia</i>, it describes fishing conditions at Bognor pier and recommends using the &lsquo;paternoster&rsquo; pattern of stringing hooks.  </div>
